Strong priorities for fragile states
LONDON/MONROVIA/KIGALI – No country has been spared the aftershocks of COVID-19.
However, the most "fragile" countries in the world face a set of particularly complex issues.
Indeed, before the pandemic began, countries such as Yemen, Sudan, Haiti, Sierra Leone, Myanmar, Afghanistan, Venezuela, and others were already struggling with poverty, conflict, corruption, and weak public administration.
Today, these elements leave these countries ill-equipped to manage the COVID-19 crisis.
What every country needs in order to overcome the pandemic is precisely what is lacking in fragile states: a government capable of developing and implementing an action plan, an effective police force to enforce the rules, social programs that provide funding, supplies, and health services to care for the infected.
The lack of state resources becomes immediately apparent in the field of public health.
While Europe has 4,000 intensive care beds per million inhabitants, several regions in Africa have only five per million inhabitants.
The Mali has only three fans for the entire country.
An effective response also requires trust in the State's intervention.
However, in addition to its lack of resources, the public administration of most fragile states does not benefit from much public support.
In countries recovering from conflict or suffering from endemic corruption, many people will refrain from supporting the government even if it proves capable of governing.
A strong private sector is also an essential component of effective and solid states.
Citizens should be able to work to support their families, and the state should be able to collect tax revenues to assist those who cannot do so.
However, in fragile states, the formal economy is not sufficiently present to meet these needs.
Earlier during the crisis, there was hope that some fragile states would avoid the worst health consequences of COVID-19 due to the demographic weight of the youth and their geographical remoteness.
However, from our perspective as co-chairs of the new Council on State Fragility, we must note that this was not the case.
In the past few weeks, Sudan, South Sudan, Somalia, and Yemen have all experienced infection and mortality rates rivaling those of developed countries that were initially hit by the coronavirus.
Worse still, the economic consequences of the pandemic will certainly be more severe for fragile states. These consequences will not only result from national lockdowns but also from what is happening abroad.
Trade with countries like China has declined, remittances from expatriates have dropped, prices of basic products and oil revenues have collapsed, and deficits are accumulating.
Since fragile states rely on imports for most of their food supply, there is increasing talk of "hunger" and even "famine."
We should now have realized that the problems of less developed countries are increasingly becoming global issues, whether in the form of mass migrations, criminal or terrorist organizations, or economic repercussions.
Given that half of the vulnerable populations will live in fragile states by 2030, these problems will not cease to worsen.
That is why the Council on State Fragility has made it an absolute priority to draw attention to the specific challenges that these countries must overcome.
The council, composed of former global leaders, ministers, diplomats, business figures, academics, and heads of development organizations, will combine cutting-edge research with meticulous political knowledge. Its aim is to guide national and international political decision-makers on how fragile states will emerge from this crisis and how they will tackle their broader and deeper challenges.
Decentralization, adaptability, and the wise use of data will be essential.
For example, it is widely proven that the "targeted containment" of local outbreaks is often more appropriate than national containment.
Such knowledge could prove crucial for fragile states.
Nevertheless, we must act quickly before the critical phase of the pandemic in the West comes to an end and the sense of urgency fades.
We propose five recommendations.
First, access to social protection should be simpler and faster.
Sometimes, it will mean universal eligibility rather than precise targeting.
Mobile telephone networks should be used to gather information on immediate needs and to make regular small payments (although of limited duration).
Secondly, national food production should be encouraged.
For example, Sierra Leone, which cultivated rice, has become increasingly dependent in recent decades.
More generally, Africa accounts for 60% of the unused arable land in the world.
Local initiatives for the production of basic crops must be rapidly expanded to a much larger scale.
Thirdly, once vaccine production begins, the international community must ensure that fragile states are not excluded from the market by more developed countries.
When the threat is a contagious pathogen, no country is safe unless all are.
We must advocate for and accelerate the production of multiple vaccines to ensure rapid and widespread distribution.
Fourthly, businesses in fragile states need immediate assistance.
As the most involved financial institutions in international development note, small businesses in less developed countries are often overlooked and suffer the adverse effects of broader goals and rules (since it is easier to achieve a goal by investing in large-scale projects in larger economies).
Nevertheless, it is precisely these small businesses that need more significant investments.
Finally, the G20 should do more to support heavily indebted fragile states that are forced to choose between paying their foreign creditors or saving their population.
It is expected that countries receiving bilateral development aid will have to repay approximately 40 billion dollars to private and public creditors this year alone.
In order to prevent this financial shock, we urge all members of the G20 to temporarily suspend accumulated debts not only until next year, but also until the end of the crisis.
Moreover, it is crucial that all fragile states obtain emergency financing to support their efforts to contain COVID-19 and mitigate its economic repercussions — particularly those countries that do not usually have access to financing from the World Bank or the International Monetary Fund.
The COVID-19 pandemic will exacerbate existing problems in all fragile states around the world.
However, if the international community reacts promptly, we will be able to mitigate the worst consequences of the pandemic.
If there is indeed a lesson to be learned from this crisis, it is that livelihoods and lives will be saved if we move faster than the virus.
